    "title": "THUNDER STORM",
    "slug": "thunder-storm",
    "excerpt": "I love thunder storm",
    "body": "<p><strong>thunderstorm</strong>, a violent short-lived <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/weather\"><u>weather</u></a> disturbance that is almost always associated with <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/lightning-meteorology\"><u>lightning</u></a>, <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/thunder\"><u>thunder</u></a>, <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb\" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/dense\"><u>dense</u></a> clouds, heavy <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/rain\"><u>rain</u></a> or <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/hail-meteorology\"><u>hail</u></a>, and strong gusty <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/wind\"><u>winds</u></a>. Thunderstorms arise when layers of warm, moist air rise in a large, swift updraft to cooler regions of the <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/atmosphere\"><u>atmosphere</u></a>. There the moisture contained in the updraft condenses to form towering cumulonimbus <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Clouds-play-by-Aristophanes\"><u>clouds</u></a> and, eventually, <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/precipitation\"><u>precipitation</u></a>. Columns of cooled air then sink earthward, striking the ground with strong downdrafts and horizontal winds. At the same time, <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/electric-charge\"><u>electrical charges</u></a> accumulate on cloud particles (water droplets and ice). <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/lightning-meteorology\"><u>Lightning</u></a> discharges occur when the accumulated electric charge becomes sufficiently large. Lightning heats the <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/air\"><u>air</u></a> it passes through so intensely and quickly that <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/shock-wave\"><u>shock waves</u></a> are produced; these shock waves are heard as claps and rolls of thunder. On occasion, severe thunderstorms are accompanied by swirling <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb\" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/vortices\"><u>vortices</u></a> of air that become concentrated and powerful enough to form <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"md-crosslink \" href=\"https://www.britannica.com/science/tornado\"><u>tornadoes</u></a>.</p>",
